DPRK to react to unreasonable "countermeasure" with toughest stance 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 19 (KCNA) -- U.S. Secretary of State Powell said that the nuclear issue of the DPRK should be brought to the UNSC and "concrete countermeasures including economic sanctions would be seriously considered."
 This fully represented the hostile intention of the Bush administration to shift the responsibility for the nuclear issue on the Korean Peninsula, which was authored and has been hyped by it, and the resultant serious developments on to the DPRK and use the un platform as was the case with the IAEA for internationalizing its campaign to pressurize, isolate and stifle the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. is entirely to blame for the nuclear issue on the Korean Peninsula. This issue was unreasonably put on the U.N. agenda to be discussed there in the past as the U.S. instigated the IAEA to create artificial difficulties and complexity in the way of settling the issue. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 But the crisis over the nuclear issue on the Korean Peninsula in 1993 was settled through negotiations between the DPRK and the U.S., not by the UN. This historical fact proves that the issue can be settled only through equal and fair dialogue and negotiations between the DPRK and the U.S., not by any third party's unjust intervention. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the United Nations wants to show its principled stand and attitude to settle the issue with a fair concern for it, it should call into question the U.S. unreasonable DPRK policy that compelled it to take a self-defensive step to withdraw from the NPT. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. abandoned its commitments to fully normalize the political and economic relations with the DPRK, provide light water reactors to the latter and supply heavy oil to it, thus unilaterally and totally ditching the DPRK-U.S. Agreed Framework and causing an acute shortage of electricity to the DPRK. It also singled out the DPRK as a target of its preemptive nuclear attack after listing it as part of an "axis of evil", creating extremely grave danger of a nuclear war on the Korean Peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Such act of threatening the DPRK's vital right is a crime against humanity quite contrary to the spirit of the UN Charter for peace of humankind as it is intolerable political violence in the modern society. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the U.S. drives the developments to the extremes, turning aside the DPRK's fair and aboveboard proposal for settling the issue in a peaceful way through the conclusion of a non-aggression treaty with the U.S. and clamoring for any "countermeasures," the DPRK will be left with no option but to counter it with the toughest stance.

U.S. shameless threat lambasted 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 19 (KCNA) -- Recently the U.S. bellicose elements blustered that the "nuclear issue" of the DPRK "should be brought to the UN Security Council" and "concrete countermeasures including economic sanctions against the DPRK would be considered there."
 In this regard Rodong Sinmun today says in a commentary it fully revealed the shameless nature and wicked intention of the U.S. to internationalize the DPRK's "nuclear issue" in a bid to brand it as a "criminal" and stifle it at any cost. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The nuclear issue and the present situation on the Korean Peninsula are entirely attributable to the U.S. imperialists' hostile policy toward the DPRK, the commentary says, and goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is none other than the U.S. that compelled the DPRK to withdraw from the NPT. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If somebody wants to remind the united nations of the nuclear issue, he should call into question the U.S. hostile policy to stifle the DPRK, which compelled it to take a self-defence step. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 However, the U.S., the assailant, is taking such a high-handed and menacing attitude towards the DPRK, the victim, just like a thief crying "stop the thief", blustering that it would bring the nuclear issue of the DPRK to the UNSC and take sanctions against the DPRK. This is the height of shamelessness. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is ridiculous of the U.S. to abuse the name of the un for attaining its dirty goal for aggression. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 "Sanctions" or military pressure can never work on the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the United States continues to drive the situation to the extremes while branding the DPRK as a "criminal", we will be left with no option but to react to it with the toughest stance. The U.S. will be held wholly responsible for the ensuing consequences.

Homage paid to Kim Il Sung by special envoy of Russian President 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 19 (KCNA) -- A. P. Losyukov, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs of Russia who is a special envoy of the Russian President, Sunday visited the Kumsusan Memorial Palace to pay homage to President Kim Il Sung.
 Present there were Losyukov and his party and Andrei Karlov, Russian Ambassador to the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Also present were Kung Sok Ung, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs of the DPRK, and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They paid respectful homage to the president who lies in state for perpetuity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then they looked round with keen interest the orders, medals and certificates of honorary titles he received from the DPRK and different countries of the world, the mourning hall reminding them of those days when the Korean people deeply grieved over the greatest loss of the nation and a train and a car he used for on-site guidance and foreign visits and in the last period of his life. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The special envoy made the following entry in the visitor's book: I pay high tribute to comrade Kim Il Sung, the founder of the DPRK and an outstanding statesman, who exerted consistent efforts for the development of the relations of friendship and cooperation between the Korean and Russian peoples.

Special envoy of Russian President feted 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 19 (KCNA) -- The DPRK Government gave a reception Saturday in honor of A. O. Losyukov, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs who is a special envoy of the Russian President on a visit to the DPRK.
 First Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kang Sok Ju in a speech made at the reception noted with appreciation that the Russian leadership's dispatch of the special envoy to the DPRK at a time when a dangerous situation is prevailing on the Korean Peninsula due to the U.S. moves to stifle the DPRK proceeded from the good faith and goodwill stand to settle the present situation on the Korean Peninsula at any cost, setting store by the DPRK-Russian relations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK and the U.S. should sit face to face to solve the nuclear issue on the Korean Peninsula as it was authored by the latter and the internationalization of this issue would make the prospect of its settlement more complicated and gloomy, he said, and continued: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We will in the future, too, set store by the DPRK-Russian relations based on the special relationship between the two top leaders, steadily boost them and work together with Russia for the peace and security on the Korean Peninsula and in other parts of the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A.P. Losyukov in a speech made at the reception said that the Russia-DPRK talks held today are of weighty importance, adding that they helped have a better understanding of each other's stands on the situation prevailing on the Korean Peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Noting that the interaction and cooperation between Russia and the DPRK have become more brisk than ever before in recent years, he said that this has opened a new stage in the development of the bilateral relations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The meetings of the two top leaders based on the particular relationship have provided a solid foundation of boosting the Russia-DPRK relations and deepening the bilateral understanding and confidence, he added. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the reception on invitation were the party of the special envoy, Russian Ambassador to the DPRK Andrei Karlov and staff members of the Russian embassy. Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kung Sok Ung and other officials concerned were present there.

Kim Jong Il stresses need to firmly defend territorial airspace of country 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 18 (KCNA) - General Secretary Kim Jong Il yesterday inspected flying unit no. 860 of the KPA.
 During his inspection he expressed satisfaction over that all the servicepersons of the unit are firmly defending the territorial airspace of the country to cope with the evermore undisguised war moves of the enemy, highly appreciated their feats and set forth tasks that would serve as guidelines in increasing the combat power of the unit. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The unit was honored with field guidance given by President Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Il scores of times. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Jong Il said the unit that has covered the road of victory and honor under the meticulous guidance and care of the president is a flying unit with a long tradition of struggle as it has produced dozens of DPRK heroes and many persons of great feats, adding that the undying feats the president performed for the strengthening and development of the nation's air force would shine long in the history of the matchless air force. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He learned in detail about the unit's performance of duty and training and looked round a servicemen's hall, a mess and other places. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He met with the officers and men of the unit to give a warm pep talk to them before posing for a photograph with them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He went to a sub-unit honored with the title of "O Jung Hup's Seventh Regiment" under the unit to take warm care of the living of the pilots with paternal love. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He met with a private third class Kim Myong Hui, one of the young girls who laid bouquets of wild flowers prepared with much care before the monument to the president's on-the-spot guidance on a remote roadside, missing Generalissimo Kim Il Sung, on June 22, 1996, the story about whom touched the people so deeply. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Looking back with deep emotion on the day he was deeply impressed to see the wildflowers laid before the monument to the on-the-spot guidance while he was passing through Yonha-ri, Sinuiju, he was very pleased to see Kim Myong Hui standing at the post defending the country. He highly praised her invariable loyalty and patriotic devotion. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then he visited pilot Hong Thae Sik's family. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Hong and his wife had the great honor of receiving profound loving care from Kim Jong Il when he dropped in at their room on August 28, 2001 during their pleasant vacation at the Kalma rest home of the KPA. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Speaking highly of Hong's long and devoted service at the air force unit, he told Hong to bring up their children as good pilots and soldiers to make his family a family of servicepersons who defend the country with arms. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Jong Il saw an art performance given by airmen of the sub- unit and had a photograph taken with the sub-unit's servicepersons. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He was accompanied by generals of the KPA Ri Myong Su, Hyon Chol Hae and Pak Jae Gyong and secretaries Kim Kuk Thae and Kim Ki Nam and first vice-department directors Ri Yong Chol, Jang Song Thaek and Choe Chun Hwang of the WPK Central Committee

KCNA assails Japanese Prime Minister's visit to "Yasukuni Shrine"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 18 (KCNA) -- Japanese Prime Minister Koizumi's January 14 visit to the "Yasukuni Shrine" is under fire by the international community.
 This was his third visit in less than two years after his assumption of office. It is intolerable as it is intended to call back the departed soul of militarists and justify the aggression and all the crimes Japan committed against Asian countries in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He was reported to have told media persons prior to his visit that he was going to visit the shrine in peace, lost in the thought that Japan would not start a war again. It is, indeed, a foolish attempt to mislead the fair public opinion critical of visits to the shrine. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 How can the visit to the shrine, a symbol of militarism, bring peace and security to the Korean people and other people of the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Koizumi's visit is an open challenge to the Korean people and all other people of Asia who hope that Japan will not repeat its history of aggression, its blood-stained history. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 His misbehavior is quite contrary to the spirit of the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang Declaration, in which Japan admitted, in a spirit of humility, the facts of history that it caused tremendous damage and sufferings to the Korean people through its colonial rule in the past and expressed deep remorse and heartfelt apology. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The state relations between the DPRK and Japan can never be normalized as long as Japan persistently works to revive militarism while covering up its past history in which it imposed great misfortune and sufferings upon the Korean people and committed unprecedented crimes against Korea in the last century. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese politicians should stop the anachronistic moves to justify the unprecedented crimes committed against the Korean people and opt for clearly liquidating Japan's past as early as possible in line with the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang Declaration.
